-- Sub-Saharan African Equities: First Bank and George Williamson Are Active
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-06-25T15:26:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-25/sub-saharan-african-equities-first-bank-and-george-williamson-are-active.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  increased
for a third day, rising 0.1 percent to 1,646.99 at the close in
Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  rose less than 0.1 percent to close
at 73.85, a third day of gains. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  declined 0.7 percent to 25,154.26 in Lagos,
according to data on the exchange’s website. The index dropped
2.7 percent this week.  
 Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  dropped for a fourth
day, falling 1.3 percent to 751.22 in the capital Windhoek. The
 Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  declined the most since
June 9, falling 2.1 percent to 6.567.73.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 First Bank of Nigeria Plc  (FIRSTBAN NL) rose the most in
more than a month, rallying 33 kobo, or 2.5 cents, to 13.34
naira. First Bank, the country’s second-biggest lender by market
value, is in discussions to buy a stake in a Chinese bank,
ThisDay reported yesterday, citing Chief Executive Officer Bisi
Onasanya, who didn’t name the lender.  
 George Williamson Kenya Ltd.  (GWKL KN), a tea producer,
climbed to the highest level in more than three months,
advancing 19 shillings, or 8.8 percent, to 236 shillings. The
company reported a more than seven-fold surge in profit for the
year through March to 876.1 million shillings ($10.8 million).  
